<TEXT>
residents waited behind boarded windows or 
fled to shelters early friday while typhoon russ battered the 
island with winds topping 100 mph 
there were no immediate reports of injuries or damage officials 
said 
russ was the strongest typhoon to hit this western pacific 
island in more than a decade it toppled trees pushed surf to more 
than 20 feet high and made movement around the 30milelong island 
virtually impossible 
everybodys just sitting tight guam civil defense spokesman 
mike franquez said well wait for the winds to pass and then 
assess the damage 
about 145000 people live on guam the last storm to cause major 
damage here was typhoon pamela in 1976 
winds were clocked at 90 mph with gusts to 115 mph when the 
storm made its closest pass before dawn said navy capt dieter 
rudolph commander of the joint typhoon warning center 
the wind readings were taken at the typhoon center near the 
north end of northsouth lying island the storms center brushed 
guams south coast and southern areas were pummelled by the 
strongest winds 
the storms maximum sustained winds were 145 mph with gusts to 
175 mph rudolph said it was moving westnorthwest at 13 mph 
about 2300 people went to shelters at schools the windows of 
most buildings had been boarded up franquez said 
to avert the potential problem of dangling live wires if power 
lines break electricity was shut off to most of the island water 
also was cut off some coastal roads were closed because the high 
surf left them strewn with debris 
theres downed power lines downed trees flooded streets 
said dave ecret of kgum radio its just an eerie kind of 
feeling 
