<TEXT>
two courts thursday denied a request to 
have nancy cruzans feeding tube reconnected as demonstrators kept 
a vigil at the hospital where she is dying and launched new legal 
efforts to keep her alive 
yvette williams who cares for severely disabled children asked 
the courts to require the state to provide nourishment to ms 
cruzan who has been in a persistent vegetative state since a 1983 
traffic accident 
miss williams request was denied by the missouri supreme court 
and the missouri court of appeals 
she was represented by mario mandina of the antieuthanasia 
group lawyers for life mandina said he planned to return to the 
missouri supreme court to seek a rehearing 
at least two new legal attempts to force ms cruzans feeding 
tube to be reconnected were launched 
ms cruzan 33 is the central figure in a righttodie case 
that went to the us supreme court and culminated dec 14 with a 
probate judges decision that her parents could order her feeding 
tube removed 
the tube was withdrawn hours later doctors estimated ms cruzan 
would die within two weeks without food and water her condition 
deteriorated thursday 
our laws protect life miss williams who lives in kansas 
city said in a prepared statement what is happening here 
offends me i cannot in conscience be a party to the killing of 
nancy cruzan 
protesters from the antiabortion movement have converged since 
the tube was removed on the missouri rehabilitation center where 
ms cruzan is looked after in this southwestern missouri town of 
3400 the protesters say the cruzan case is an extension of their 
cause 
police arrested 19 demonstrators tuesday after they refused to 
leave they remained thursday in the lawrence county jail 
about 15 protesters gathered thursday on the porch of the 
hospital where they said they would maintain a vigil until ms 
cruzan dies 
the supreme court rejected ms williams request in a 
twosentence order it was signed by judge edward robertson who 
wrote the courts november 1988 decision that denied a request from 
ms cruzans parents joe and joyce cruzan for authority to remove 
the tube providing their daughter food and water 
that ruling sent the case to the us supreme court which ruled 
in june in its first righttodie case that missouri could require 
clear and convincing evidence ms cruzan would not want to live 
in the vegetative state 
at a hearing last month former coworkers testified ms cruzan 
had said she would never want to live like a vegetable 
in a separate effort to have ms cruzans feeding tube 
reconnected a civil rights lawsuit was filed in us district 
court in springfield by the rev pat mahoney director of the 
center for christian activism in boca raton fla 
nancy cruzan has no advocate no one to stand for her no one 
to appeal this decision mahoney said 
a hearing was set for friday 
