president patricio aylwin on thursday 
called in the army commander and former chilean ruler gen augusto 
pinochet to demand an explanation of why the military refused to 
leave its barracks the day before 
as pinochet entered and left the downtown presidential palace 
hundreds of people demonstrated against him chanting antimilitary 
slogans and urging aylwin to demand his resignation 
pinochet said the military moves wednesday were just an 
exercise but government officials and others had described them as 
a protest over news reports on an illegal financial institution 
involving highranking officers 
the chilean media has widely reported on the scandal for weeks 
alleging that a savings and loan operation run by people in the 
military resulted in losses for individual depositors that ranged 
as high as 500000 
wednesdays action by the soldiers was the first instance of 
military unrest since pinochets military rule ended nine months 
ago it raised fears that the military might challenge civilian 
control 
but the civilian government said democracy was not in danger 
the goverment said thursday in a communique that pinochet spoke 
to the president during an hourlong meeting at the presidential 
palace where the former military ruler was summoned by his 
civilian successor 
aylwin the communique said required from the commander in 
chief and explanation for the unusual measures taken by the 
institution he commands 
pinochet explained that it was a security readiness and 
coordination exercise which ended this morning and it had no 
extrainstitutional connotations the brief communique said 
as he left the presidential palace a smiling relaxed pinochet 
also told reporters the confining to barracks was an exercise 
asked why the goverment was not informed beforehand he replied 
we dont have to tell the government this is army business the 
army has not bothered anybody has not taken to the streets 
aylwin is constitutionally prohibited from firing pinochet who 
remained commander of the 60000man army after handing over the 
presidency to the new civilian government 
meanwhile politicians from left to right on thursday expressed 
full support for the countrys newly restored democracy 
what we all want is to maintain the democratic system and i 
believe no one should do anything against it said jose pinera a 
former cabinet minister under pinochet and a close ally of the 
75yearold general 
sergio bitar a socialist leader called the military action a 
blackmail and a threat he said nobody in chile wants the 
consolidation of democracy to be halted 
