<DOCNO> AP901220-0010 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
new medicines tailored to block a troublesome body 
chemical appear to stop allergic reactions before they start and 
could also provide relief to millions of asthma and hay fever 
sufferers scientists reported today 
the drugs still in their experimental stages thwart the bodys 
production of substances known as leukotrienes thy are among the 
chief culprits in triggering common allergic reactions 
what makes this important is that its a new way of treating 
asthma said dr jeffrey m drazen of bostons beth israel 
hospital other drugs put out the fire once its started we 
havent had a way to prevent the problem in the first place which 
is what these drugs do 
unlike many other allergy medicines these drugs appear to have 
no side effects if they prove safe and effective in additional 
testing they could have widespread use 
asthma and hay fever are incredibly prevalent diseases these 
are potential approaches that could impact on the lives of 25 
percent of the people in the united states said dr michael 
kaliner of the national institute of allergy and infectious 
diseases 
doctors said the drugs could supplement or replace several of 
the asthma drugs already in use such as cromolyn and theophylline 
some of these drugs have side effects including tremors nausea 
vomiting headaches and drowsiness 
an estimated 35 million to 40 million americans get hay fever 
and 12 million to 15 million have asthma 
this is an area people have been studying for a long time 
said dr suzanne hurd of the national heart lung and blood 
institute this is the first example that we might have some 
payoff here its very promising and exciting 
dr howard r knapp of the university of iowa used the 
experimental abbott laboratories drug zileuton to prevent hay fever 
symptoms in people allergic to ragweed and grasses 
in the other studies researchers from beth israel used the same 
drug to prevent asthma induced by breathing cold air and doctors 
from mcmaster university in hamilton ontario gave the merck sharp 
and dohme drug venzair to prevent asthma triggered by exercise 
the three studies were published in todays new england journal 
of medicine 
elsewhere doctors are experimenting with similar 
leukotrieneblocking drugs against such ailments as rheumatoid 
arthritis the skin disease psoriasis and the digestive illness 
ulcerative colitis 
leukotrienes are known to cause tightening of the air passages 
in the lungs and increase mucous production in the nose but until 
the recent development of drugs that block leukotrienes scientists 
could not prove their importance in allergic reactions 
knapp gave the drug to eight people with hay fever when they 
were exposed to ragweed or grass seven of them had a lot less 
congestion 
in the beth israel study doctors tested zileuton on 13 people 
whose asthma is triggered by cold dry air the drug increased 
their tolerance of cold by 47 percent 
in the mcmaster study dr patrick j manning and others tested 
venzair on 12 people who regularly got asthma during exercise the 
treatment reduced their asthma by 70 percent and in three people 
prevented it entirely 
</TEXT>
