<DOCNO> AP901220-0013 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a treatment intended to weaken the immune system 
temporarily to prevent orga rejection has been linked with a 
sharply increased cancer risk in heart transplant patients doctors 
reported today 
doctors from loyola university medical center said 11 percent of 
their patients who got the treatment developed lymphoma a blood 
cell cancer the cancers typically developed a month or two after 
the surgery and were rapidly fatal 
the treatment called okt3 is a tailormade antibody that 
attacks a variety of white blood cells that play a key role in 
making the body reject the transplanted organ okt3 gained 
widespread use about three years ago 
the new study shows that even if okt3 prevents rejection and 
this is in doubt the benefit comes at a high cost 
we found that the addition of okt3 was statistically strongly 
linked with a sharp increase in this form of cancer said dr 
lode j swinnen who directed the study 
people who get transplanted organs routinely receive a variety 
of medicines that temporarily weaken their defenses this is 
intended to thwart the bodys tendency to attack the alien organ 
doctors have long recognized that these medicines increase the 
risk of blood cancer however swinnens study published in the 
new england journal of medicine found that okt3 heightened the 
risk dramatically 
of 79 heart transplant patients who got the treatment at loyola 
nine developed lymphoma and six of them died 
in an accompanying editorial dr israel penn of the university 
of cincinnati medical center said the use of these drugs and the 
development of cancer indicate that we have much to learn about 
walking the tightrope between preventing rejection and inducing 
lymphomas 
but overall he said only about 1 percent of all transplant 
recipients die of cancer penn said the risk should not stop 
transplants but instead should spur research to find better 
alternative drugs 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

