<DOCNO> AP901220-0016 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
white house opposition is prompting the 
environmental protection agency to scuttle proposed requirements 
for recycling by trash incinerators 
the agency decided wednesday to delete from incinerator 
regulations to be issued dec 31 a provision that would require at 
least 25 percent of incoming garbage be recycled as a condition for 
a burning permit 
the recycling requirement met strong opposition earlier 
wednesday during a meeting of the presidents council on 
competitiveness an interagency panel chaired by vice president dan 
quayle that reviews regulatory proposals for their impact 
in the face of the stiff criticism epa administrator william 
reilly agreed to withdraw the recycling provision although he 
argued in favor of it during the session said administration 
sources familiar with the white house discussions they spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
in a telephone interview reilly confirmed the decision to 
withdraw the recycling requirement in the rules that will establish 
new standards for air emissions for garbage incinerators 
we will not propose source separation of at least 25 percent 
in these new standards he said 
reilly said it was decided that the planned regulation was not 
the appropriate vehicle for a major mandatory recycling program 
with significant potential to disrupt local government plans for 
incineration programs 
environmentalists had praised the epa when it included the 
recycling provision in a proposed incineration rule a year ago 
they argued the provision would reduce the amount of wastes burned 
and therefore air pollution 
this is a major environmental retreat david doniger an 
attorney for the natural resources defense council said after 
wednesdays action the administration is retreating on its own 
commitment for recycling 
administration sources said reilly had tried to enlist support 
for the recycling provision and reiterated his defense of the 
requirement at the meeting of the regulatory review panel 
among those reported arguing against mandatory recycling for 
incinerators were henson moore the deputy energy secretary 
richard darman the white house budget director and michael 
boskin chairman of the council of economic advisers the sources 
said 
they maintained that the costs of recycling a quarter of the 
garbage destined for incineration outweighed the benefits and could 
hinder development of wastetoenergy programs in some communities 
they argued that the issue of recycling should be dealt with 
separately next year when federal laws on waste disposal come up 
for reconsideration in congress 
the epa incinerator regulation will set stricter air pollution 
standards for trash burning at a time when an increasing number of 
communities see incineration as a means of dealing with a growing 
shortage of landfill space especially in the east 
reilly argued forcefully for the recycling measure in 
cabinetlevel discussions but when no compromise could be reached 
the matter was turned over to the quayle review group reilly could 
have appealed the matter to president bush but declined to do so 
the waste disposal industry had opposed the recycling provision 
and argued that it could jeopardize some potential garbage 
incineration programs which already are often highly 
controversial 
waste combustion is now seen as a costeffective and 
environmentally sound means of solid waste management for many 
communities this could change if burdensome and perhaps costly 
recycling requirements are a condition allen moore president of 
the national solid waste management association recently wrote 
reilly 
the group represents 2500 companies involved in waste disposal 
</TEXT>
