<TEXT>
moments after foreign minister eduard shevardnadze 
stunned the kremlin today by announcing his resignation soviet 
political commentators began debating why he did it 
was it an emotional reaction to the rise of the more 
conservative forces in the nation was it part of some 
longbuilding disagreement with the military over the soviet 
unions increasingly independent foreign policy 
or was it as tass commentator andrei orlov wrote a clever 
ruse to somehow split the conservative forces and scare the 
reformers into giving president mikhail s gorbachev the support he 
needs to impose presidential rule 
whatever the reasons shevardnadzes departure represents a 
serious blow to gorbachev 
not only is he losing a shrewd diplomat who shaped soviet 
foreign policy on afghanistan and nuclear disarmament but also a 
key ally among reformers 
as another tass commentator put it gorbachev has so far been 
able to avoid open conflicts with the truly democratic wing in the 
soviet leadership in his middleoftheroad approaches to domestic 
and international problems 
the resignation comes at a critical time for gorbachev as he 
weighs taking harsh actions to hold the soviet union together amid 
a worsening economy against the need to preserve the democratic 
reforms that he has launched 
it also comes during the persian gulf crisis and less than two 
months before a summit with president bush to conclude a treaty to 
slash nuclear arsenals possibly a contentious issue among 
hardline military officers 
in this light shevardnadzes move could almost be seen as an 
act of disloyalty but this would be out of character for 
shevardnadze who was widely admired for his personal modesty 
integrity and above all unflagging loyalty to gorbachev a 
friendship that dates back to their teens 
foreign ministry spokesman vitaly churkin said that in 
resigning shevardnadze wanted to add his deep feelings of 
respect and friendship for gorbachev 
shevardnadzes motive most likely is the most obvious 
possibility he wants to send a strong message to gorbachev and 
other reformers in the soviet union about the dangers of 
dictatorship and instability 
churkin let one hint fall when he told reporters that 
shevardnadze spent many sleepless nights before making the 
decision 
the minister believes that this move made by a man of his 
status and authority will become a serious warning to all that 
people will soberly and quietly look at themselves and the state of 
affairs churkin said only the people can prevent dictatorial 
elements from taking power 
tass noted that shevardnadze has spoken often in the past about 
the need for stability at home 
in his addresses to parliament and a number of interviews 
shevardnadze said repeatedly that economic weakness and mounting 
instability could reduce to naught all his countrys efforts on the 
international scene the tass commentary said 
in noting this tass said shevardnadze may have been influenced 
by wednesdays statement to the congress of peoples deputies by 
prime minister nikolai ryzhkov who said perestroika as 
originally conceived has failed to materialize and not even a 
cabinet reshuffle would ensure its success 
the irony is that thousands of people in recent months have 
filled the streets calling for ryzhkovs resignation but he 
remains and it is shevardnadze who is stepping down 
 
</TEXT>
