<TEXT>
democrats say the white house is ignoring the 
fact that the nations population of drug addicts is bigger than 
ever as it touts a new survey that indicates a drop in casual use 
of cocaine 
while the household survey is dramatic proof that the reagan 
and bush administrations have succeeded in reducing casual use it 
is equally dramatic proof that they have failed terribly in 
reducing hardcore addiction said rep john conyers jr dmich 
we are fighting a twotiered drug war said conyers 
chairman of the house government operations committee the fact 
that daily cocaine use has risen not dropped indicates that only 
one drug war is being effectively fought the one for the educated 
and middleclass 
the drug strategy does not yet fight for our inner cities 
where addiction rates have gone up among poor people and 
minorities 
the household survey on drug abuse released wednesday found 
that current use of any illicit drug dropped 44 percent over the 
last five years from 23 million in 1985 to 129 million this year 
the survey also found a huge 72 percent drop in current use of 
cocaine the most virulent drug of the 1980s the number of current 
cocaine users fell from 58 million in 1985 to 16 million this 
year current use also called casual use means using a 
drug at least once a month 
the magnitude of the progress is impressive indeed 
president bush said at a news conference releasing the survey 
findings the news we have today suggests that our hard work is 
paying off and our national strategy is having an effect 
however there also was bad news 
the number of people who use cocaine daily or almost daily rose 
by 37 percent over five years from 246000 in 1985 to 336000 this 
year according to the survey sponsored by the national institute 
on drug abuse or nida 
the number of current crack cocaine users has remained stable 
the past two years at about a halfmillion and the survey 
undercounts them according to nida director charles r schuster 
while current use of any illicit drug fell during the past five 
years from 12 percent to 64 percent of all americans age 12 and 
above the rates remained higher among several groups young adults 
age 1825 years 149 percent the unemployed 14 percent blacks 
