<TEXT>
a temporary ban has been placed on siberian 
log imports because of the threat of introducing agricultural pests 
into the united states the agricultural department said today 
the soviet union first shipped siberian logs to the united 
states last summer under tightly controlled test conditions said 
james w glosser administrator of the departments animal and 
plant health inspection service 
we inspected the logs upon entry and found two potentially 
harmful pests he said since then we have learned that 
siberian raw wood can harbor over 100 organisms not native to the 
united states 
based on these findings glosser said further imports of the 
logs will be put off until more information is available 
glosser said the duration of the ban will depend on the results 
of a risk assessment which will examine the possible pest hazards 
of siberian log imports to us agriculture 
we are currently working with regulatory and forestry 
officials from oregon california and washington usdas forest 
service and the timber industry to gather and examine available 
data on siberian logs he said 
after the assessment is completed in early 1991 glosser said 
agency officials will evaluate the need for developing regulations 
to restrict or prohibit the entry of siberian logs 
