<TEXT>
the world health organization on thursday urged 
greater efforts to reduce the estimated 250 million cases of 
sexually transmitted infections that occur each year 
the un agency said although education and medical programs 
have helped combat the spread of infections such as gonorrhea in 
industrialized countries the number of cases in the third world 
remains unnacceptably high 
dr andre meheus a senior who official told a press conference 
that sexually transmitted infections pose an important public 
health problem and may lead to sterility infertility 
stillbirths blindness brain damage cancer or death 
a who report said the most common infection is trichomoniasis a 
parasitic infestation causing vaginal discharge in women it 
estimated there are 120 million cases each year 
the report said some 50 million cases of the bacterial infection 
chlamydia occur worldwide it said in some us inner city areas 
from 10 percent to 30 percent of sexually active young women are 
infected although it does not always produce clear clinical signs 
persistent infection can lead to infertility in some women 
who pointed out that although there are effective treatments for 
many of the infections lack of medical infrastructure in 
developing countries hinders control efforts 
the report stressed the need for more health education and 
prevention programs 
it pointed out that in sweden where all school children have 
sex education classes backed up by clinical services for 
adolescents gonorrhea and syphilis have almost disappeared 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

