<TEXT>
the justice department refused thursday to 
transfer convicted terrorist silvia baraldini to a prison in her 
native italy because she is likely to be paroled there from her 
43year us sentence 
the department informed italy by letter of its refusal to 
transfer baraldini to an italian prison under an international 
convention that allows sentenced criminals to serve time in their 
native country 
assistant attorney general robert s mueller iii said in the 
letter that baraldinis sentence for conspiring to commit a series 
of terrorist acts in the united states would be considerably if it 
fell under italian law 
the serious and violent nature of the crimes committed by ms 
baraldini in our view demand a sentence commensurate with those 
imposed by the courts in the united states mueller said the 
justice department wants to ensure baraldini serves a long sentence 
because we believe that if released ms baraldini would 
continue in criminal activities detrimental to the united states 
mueller also expressed concern over italian parole policies that 
have allowed convicted terrorists and organized crime figures to 
be furloughed or placed on work release after only relatively short 
periods of incarceration 
italy requested a justice department review of baraldinis case 
under the international convention on the transfer of sentenced 
prisoners baraldini who came to this country at age 13 retains 
italian citizenship 
she was convicted in 1983 of being part of a conspiracy by 
leftwing terrorists to rob armored cars including a 1981 holdup 
of a brinks truck near nyack ny that resulted in the death of a 
guard and two policemen 
baraldini was also convicted of racketeering for her 
participation in the 1980 armed robbery of an armored truck and the 
1979 kidnaping of prison guards to help convicted murderer joanne 
chesimard escape from a new jersey prison 
baraldini was sentenced to 40 years imprisonment and later 
received a threeyear term for criminal contempt because she 
refused to answer questions to a grand jury investigating leftwing 
terrorism 
the justice department said that it had information baraldini 
was still in communication with fellow members of the terrorist may 
19th organization and would assist them if released from prison 
muellers letter said authorities also had information 
indicating that baraldini may have participated in a series of 
bombings in new york and chicago by the faln a puerto rican 
separatist group 
these bombings included a 1975 blast that killed four people in 
new york the department said 
mueller said the justice department might reconsider its 
decision if baraldini expressed remorse for her crimes and 
cooperated with investigations of terrorist fugitives 
alternatively if we could be assured ms baraldini would 
serve a sentence in italy equivalent to that imposed by the judges 
here we would of course reconsider this decision mueller 
said 
baraldini is being held at the marianna federal correctional 
institution in marianna fla 
