<TEXT>
the next soviet foreign minister will face a 
different world than eduard a shevardnadze took on five years ago 
but the possible candidates all appear to be dedicated followers of 
the policy he set down 
although gorbachev could reach outside the foreign ministry for 
a replacement speculation focuses on the foreign policy 
establishment they have the kind of training shevardnadze lacked 
when mikhail s gorbachev appointed him in the summer of 1985 to 
take over for andrei a gromyko 
unlike shevardnadzes crusade for change in the last five years 
the next foreign minister will need to maintain and cultivate the 
soviet unions new role as friend of the united states a mediator 
in international disputes and partner in cooperation with europe 
and the former members of the oviet bloc 
the new foreign minister still will face old guard bureaucrats 
in some departments at the foreign ministry as he navigates new 
relations with israel the vatican japan south korea and germany 
among others 
there will likely be less financial and military aid to use as 
tool of soviet policy because the government must deal with a 
crippled economy and a budget deficit 
here is a brief look at those considered prime candidates for 
the job 
yevgeny m primakov the first candidate mentioned in the soviet 
press after shevardnadzes resignation is a 61yearold former 
professor known most recently for his shuttle diplomacy to iraq and 
the search for a solution to the persian gulf crisis 
his effort failed after several meetings with iraqi president 
saddam hussein reported to be a longtime friend but still it 
heightened his status as a savvy envoy who knows his war around the 
volatile middle east 
before becoming a deputy foreign minister last year primakov 
was director of the institute for world economy and international 
relations an expert on the middle and far east and with a 
doctorate in economics primakov helped devise the new thinking 
foreign policy that shevardnadze was implementing 
valentin m falin 64 became chief of the communist partys 
