president elias hrawi on thursday chose 
education minister omar karami to form a new government aiming to 
end 15 years of civil war in lebanon 
but three militia groups have expressed doubts that karami could 
carry out the task 
the presidential statement said the choice was based on the 
outcome of daylong consultations by hrawi with parliament blocs on 
a successor to prime minister salim hoss 
hoss a sunni moslem resigned with his 13monthold cabinet on 
wednesday to make way for a broadbased national reconciliation 
government karami 55 is also a sunni 
karami told reporters at hrawis residence he accepted the 
designation and would promptly begin consultations to form the new 
cabinet 
we shall form the government and the wheel of peace and unity 
will roll and i hope all will get aboard he said 
traditionally the president has been a maronite catholic the 
prime minister a sunni and the parliament speaker a shiite moslem 
hrawi met with parliament speaker hussein husseini after polling 
61 deputies of parliaments 68 surviving members on a successor to 
hoss 
the statement said hrawi then issued a presidential decree 
accepting the resignation of hoss and his 14member cabinet and 
signed another decree naming karami prime minister 
lebanese media said hrawi wants the new government formed of a 
crosssection of 30 politicians and warlords to end the civil war 
which had claimed more than 150000 lives 
but serious doubts have been voiced about the ability of karami 
a lawyer to put together such a government coalition 
karami surfaced on the political stage only three years ago 
when he inherited the leadership of the northern provincial capital 
of tripoli from his elder brother the late prime minister rashid 
karami 
the elder karami the longest serving prime minister in 
lebanons 47 years of independence was assassinated by a bomb 
explosion aboard an army helicopter in northern lebanon on june 1 
1987 
