there said thursday that saddam should not interpret the comments 
by the deputy commander of americas gulf forces as a sign the 
united states would not attack until well past the un deadline 
for withdrawal from kuwait 
lt gen calvin ah waller began the controversy in comments 
wednesday to reporters accompanying defense secretary dick cheney 
and gen colin powell the chairman of the joint chiefs of staff 
on their weeklong gulf trip 
waller said ground forces yet to arrive in the region might not 
be combatready until well into february and recommended that 
president bush delay any military action until then 
bush talked over the gulf situation privately with members of 
congress on thursday saying according to several of them that he 
believes saddam is underestimating us power and intentions 
saddam must be made aware that if we get into an armed 
situation hes going to get his ass kicked rep elton 
gallegly rcalif quoted bush as saying bushs remark was 
confirmed by another person at the meeting 
as for waller bushs spokesman marlin fitzwater said merely 
it never hurts to build in a little uncertainty about what our 
intentions are as it relates to jan 15 it doesnt cause us 
any grief to have a little uncertainty in the mind of saddam 
hussein about exactly when you might choose to enforce the un 
sanctions 
the commander of army forces in saudi arabia lt gen john 
yeosock was far more optimistic that waller in comments thursday 
clearly we are ready to perform whatever mission we are 
called upon to carry out yeosock said he promised a violent 
fast battle if war begins 
other officials did not dispute the essence of wallers 
nonreadiness assessment though there was private criticism that 
he had been too open and might have hurt the effort to persuade 
saddam that bush might order an attack on jan 15 or very soon 
thereafter 
in washington secretary of state james a baker iii said merely 
that an important principle he learned in the marine corps was that 
it is critical to preserve the element of surprise 
if nothing else wallers statements and those of other 
officials seemed to support the idea that an early attack would 
heavily feature air assaults designed to weaken iraqs war machine 
and give stillarriving us ground forces more time to prepare 
yeosock said that although iraq continues to pour troops into 
kuwait and southern iraq the reinforcements are less capable troops 
and the iraqi occupation force is near its maximumforce potential 
iraq also urged its citizens to stockpile oil in a new 
indication the iraqis were girding for war 
a pentagon spokesman in washington said an additional 10000 
us troops arrived in saudi arabia this week pushing the total 
american force to 280000 soldiers sailors airmen and marines 
the spokesman bob hall said us intelligence sources put the 
iraqi force in and around kuwait at 510000 
in saudi arabia as cheney and powell huddled in daylong 
private meetings with commanders spokesman pete williams said 
cheney was not displeased by wallers comments 
but williams issued a brief statement saying cheney would not 
reach conclusions of his own about the status of the deployment 
until the end of his fiveday trip and then unlike waller would 
share his advice only with the president 
and williams in a clear effort to attach a military threat to 
the un deadline said some of the us firepower would be at full 
strength by the deadline 
the air part of the force for example reaches its level of 
readiness earlier than the others williams said 
a senior pentagon official speaking privately said all combat 
aircraft committed to the gulf would be in place by jan 15 and 
saddam should be deeply worried about that deadline 
as for ground forces yeosock said we will do everything in 
our power to apply maximum power in minimum time to maintain the 
highest uptempo battle ever recorded 
yeosock said american forces had taken extensive steps to 
prepare for combat on a dirty battlefield in the event saddam 
uses chemical weapons 
he said iraqi forces are stacked behind each other in defensive 
lines and have dug extensive fortifications that include mine 
fields and barbed wire asked if us ground forces could crash 
through he said i wouldnt say its easy but we can do it 
in other gulf developments suggestive of war preparation on 
thursday 
ireland urged its citizens to leave the region by jan 15 and 
bangladesh asked its people to leave iraq and kuwait immediately 
turkey was requesting reinforcements from fellow nato members 
asking that a land and air force of 5000 men be in place on its 
border with iraq by jan 15 said a senior nato source in brussels 
belgium 
a spokesman for britains royal navy said two landing ships 
will join two others already in the gulf by jan 15 giving britain 
added capability for involvement in any amphibious assault on the 
coast of kuwait 
egypt sent more troops to saudi arabia part of the additional 
7000 soldiers that president hosni mubarak has pledged to 
reinforce the 20000man egyptian force in the kingdom 
