<TEXT>
a federal communications commission decision 
that the owner of a small radio station in fredonia ny can 
neither renew his license nor sell the business was upheld on 
thursday by the us court of appeals 
the fcc decided in march 1989 not to renew catoctin broadcasting 
corps license for the 250watt station wbuzam on grounds that 
owner henry serafin had discriminated in his hiring practices lied 
to the commission and held a contest in which he kept the prize 
we defer to the commissions expertise and judgment a 
threejudge panel on the appeals court wrote 
this was the first time in a decade that the fcc had pulled a 
license on character grounds only about 100 stations have lost 
their licenses since the fcc was founded in 1934 
serafin who learned of the decision thursday from the 
associated press said he did not know what he would do next 
im in shock right now he said from the station about 30 
miles south of buffalo i have to take a day or two to think this 
thing out 
he said he was considering asking the appeals court for a 
rehearing another option would be an appeal to the us supreme 
court in the meantime serafin said he could continue to 
broadcast 
in 1981 catoctins application to renew its license was 
challenged by the chatauqua county rural ministry inc the 
dunkirk ny chapter of the national association for the 
advancement of colored people and the local branch of the league 
of women voters 
among the charges against serafin was that he had discriminated 
against a black job applicant in 1980 the three groups said 
serafin had called the womans employment agency and asked dont 
you have any white girls to send me adding that the woman 
would make charcoal look white 
in running a contest at the station in 1982 serafin also 
allegedly kept the grand prize a stereo system for himself and 
gave another prize a trip to niagara falls to a favored 
advertiser 
in addition serafin repeatedly refused to make catoctins 
public file available to citizens the file contains a stations 
filings with the fcc and citizen complaints 
in 1986 an administrative law judge denied the stations 
application for renewal saying that serafin was dishonest 
untrustworthy and unreliable 
serafin appealed the ruling and the case went to an fcc review 
board the board concurred with the decision which was affirmed by 
the full commission in 1989 
