<TEXT>
what some people initially believed was 
the tusk of a circus elephant shot in 1816 was actually that of an 
iceage mastodon museum officials said thursday 
using two methods of radiocarbon dating experts confirmed the 
tusk was 10500 years old it belonged to a mastodon that roamed 
maine when indians first ventured into the region the experts 
said 
whats so exciting about these dates is that until now we have 
had no evidence to suggest that the earliest indians might have 
hunted elephants in the maine region said archaeologist bruce 
bourque of the maine state museum 
museum curator gary hoyle learned about the tusk while seeking 
items for an exhibit on prehistoric maine 
museum officials believed the tusk was that of a creature that 
lived sometime around the end of the last ice age but we had to 
prove our analysis was right before putting it on display said 
paul e rivard director of the state museum 
the tusk about 4 feet long was unearthed in the southern maine 
town of scarborough in 1959 the discovery generated considerable 
interest which faded when stories circulated that the tusk 
belonged to a circus elephant shot in 1816 
research verified the bones of the circus elephant old bet 
were exhumed after a brief burial and sent to the american museum 
of natural history in new york 
samples of the tusk then housed at the university of maine at 
presque isle were taken to the state museum for radiocarbon 
testing 
rivard said confirmation of the tusks age provides the first 
evidence that mastodons lived in maine when indians first arrived 
in the area its the only mammal bone yet to be identified from 
the end of the ice age in maine 
this is an extremely important find rivard said 
several rib bones were discovered with the tusk 31 years ago 
but they cannot be located now experts believe the rest of the 
mastodons skeleton may still be at the site 
museum officials hope to conduct more extensive study of the 
site next year rivard said 
</TEXT>
