<TEXT>
the united states on thursday joined in 
supporting a unanimous security council resolution that deplored 
israels deportation of palestinians and called for un monitoring 
of their safety 
it marked the first time the council moved to actively involve 
itself and the secretarygeneral in protecting palestinians in the 
israelioccupied territories seized in the 1967 middle east war 
arab diplomats called it a major step forward in achieving 
international protection of palestinins 
at the same time washington achieved a diplomatic victory over 
arab and nonaligned states in the council by preventing any 
reference to a middle east peace conference in the resolution the 
us demand had held up the vote for weeks 
instead the issue was included in a separate nonbinding 
statement by this months council president yemen which was 
approved by the council 
thursdays 150 vote was the third time in two months that the 
united states declined to exercise its veto and shield its israeli 
ally 
its vote was seen as a move to preserve the usled 
multinational coalition arrayed against iraqs saddam hussein a 
us veto on an issue considered vital to arabs could have 
undermined their confidence in the us persian gulf mission 
diplomats said 
the resolution asks un secretarygeneral javier perez de 
cuellar to become involved in assuring the safety of palestinians 
in the territories and to monitor and observe the situation 
on an urgent basis 
it asks that un personnel and resources already in the region 
be used to help protect palestinians and that the security council 
be kept informed 
israel rejected any such deployment of un personnel and change 
of mandate of un organizations in the region to deal with 
palestinians its ambassador yoram aridor told the council we 
will not accommodate any discriminatory procedure or treatment 
the united states joined in opposing any change in the role of 
un organizations in the region 
it was not clear whether the councils call for monitoring could 
or would be carried out in view of israels oppostion 
diplomats said un personnel for any such observation team 
probably would be drawn from the un truce supervision 
organizaiton which has 291 military observers in the region or 
the un relief and works agency for palestinians in the middle 
east unrwa with a staff of 2300 staff provides social services 
for about 700000 palestinians 
israel rejects un involvement in what it calls its internal 
affairs in the territories 
plo observer m nasser alkidwa termed the resolution an 
important and substantive contribution to provide protection to the 
palestinian people under israeli occupation and contribute to 
resolution of the arabisraeli conflict 
american jewish groups denounced the us vote thursday the 
antidefamation league of bnai brith said washington fell into 
saddam husseins linkage trip it said the resolution still 
inflicts significant undeserved damage on israel 
us ambassador thomas r pickering said the resolution did not 
indicate a change in us policy on the middle east he said the 
us vote is intended to demonstrate our deep concern about 
the situation in the occupied territories 
but he also said the council ought to be willing to say to 
the palestinians that any use of violence to achieve their ends is 
plain wrong we lament the continued violence particularly in 
israel where innocent people have been the victims of numerous 
stabbings 
aridor complained bitterly in his speech that the council rushed 
to condemn israels decison to expel four moslem extremists 
believed linked to the recent murders of three jews but the 
blood of jews is not even worthy of a mention 
alkidwa of the palestine liberation organization said in an 
angry rebuttal that only israel was killing unarmed palestinians in 
the uprising against israel domination 
in thursdays separate statement the council said an 
international peace conference should facilitate a lasting 
resolution of the arabisraeli conflict but it said there was no 
agreement on when a conference shoud be held 
the united states sought to ensure the resolution did not link 
resolving the arabisraeli conflict with settlement of the gulf 
crisis 
to meet the us demand the presidential statement said the 
arabiraeli conflict was a separate issue and had to be addressed 
independently on its own merits 
unlike the resolution the presidential statement has no legal 
force 
in the resolution the security council deplores the decision 
by the government of israel the occupying power to resume 
deportation of palestinian civilians in the occupied territories 
israel has announced plans to deport four palestinians it claims 
have terrorist links 
security council efforts to address the palestinian problem 
began after the israeli police killed at least 17 palestinians at 
the alaksa mosque on the temple mount in jerusalem on oct 8 
the resolution urges israel to abide by the fourth geneva 
convention of 1949 regulating treatment of civilians in occupied 
lands israel says the convention does not apply 
the resolution asks perez de cuellar and the red cross to 
consider convening a meeting of the 164 signatories of the 
convention to consider what measures might be taken under the 
convention to help palestinians 
