and proclamations to mandela in south africa if the politicians 
prepared them 
an apology will not end the boycott smith said however 
once the foundation has been laid we can begin to work together to 
build a community where all people will be welcome 
smith criticized suarez recent statement that he regretted the 
way city officials handled the june visit of the antiapartheid 
leader saying it wasnt enough to end the boycott 
while we acknowledge that his statement is a sign of progress 
neither the content nor the context of mayor suarez statement 
indicate that it is an apology smith said 
suarez was in washington on thursday night and could not be 
reached for comment daoud said he would be very pleased to 
give mandela a proclamation of welcome and a key to his city 
we are very pleased to welcome mr mandela but not his 
friends daoud said they are enemies of the united states 
instead of the enthusiastic welcomes and ceremonies mandela 
received elsewhere on his us tour he got an official snub and 
criticism from suarez daoud and others because he refused to 
repudiate the african national congress staunch supporters fidel 
castro yasser arafat and moammar ghadhafi 
the greater miami convention and visitors bureau reported 
earlier this week that eleven groups canceled their gatherings 
some planned as far in the future as 1993 costing the city nearly 
55 million other tourism officials estimate the city has lost as 
much as 12 million 
smith said the keys and proclamations would pave the way for 
negotiations on the three other boycott demands greater business 
and employment opportunities for black citizens a review of 
federal immigration policy regarding haitians who routinely are 
detained and deported while hispanics are admitted to this country 
and a federal investigation of the miami polices violent breakup 
of a july protest by haitians 
