the 77 billion provided by the united states 
we have no overall political strategy because of all the 
competition between bureaus involved in giving aid so japan has 
had to depend on economic criteria a government official in 
charge of development programs said on condition of anonymity 
quite by accident that has worked out well 
the official said he did not expect much change although there 
is a growing percentage of purely humanitarian aid not tied to such 
commercial interests as japanese construction companies seeking to 
build overseas 
even humanitarian aid sometimes produces strange results orr 
said a huge luxury hotel was built in dhaka with japanese loans to 
bangladesh one of the worlds poorest countries 
when japan does take a moral position a combination of 
bureaucratic infighting and financial pressure can subvert it 
commercial and financial pressures probably played a part in the 
decision last july to resume a loan program to china that was 
frozen after the army assault on prodemocracy demonstrators in 
beijing in june 1989 
in march 1989 japan broke ranks with the west and resumed aid 
to burma which had cracked down on student protesters the year 
before 
the foreign ministry wanted the aid suspended but two other 
ministries finance and international trade and industry thought 
the suspension might cause financial chaos and force burma to 
default on more than 60 million in loans 
one reason japan may put more emphasis on democratic development 
in countries receiving aid is that major donor nations in the 
postcold war era need an excuse to turn away the legions of 
petitioners 
japan often said we really dont care about a regime we 
care about stability orr wrote they would give money to 
countries the us wouldnt touch with a tenfoot pole 
but today countries that lag behind in democracy and market 
progress like bulgaria and romania are going to get short shrift 
from japan 
