<TEXT>
iraq and much of the rest of the world stand 
at the brink of war threatening the most damaging confrontation 
since world war ii with unmeasurable reverberations 
to most people it looks like a historical clash 
to francis fukuyama it looks like a footnote 
fukuyama became momentarily famous in washington a year ago by 
audaciously suggesting in a learned essay that history had ended 
finis the west had won and that was that 
in fukuyamas world view the iraqi adventure is the stuff of 
headlines but not great history not what he means as history 
thats the rub he readily concedes that history by his 
definition is not the random chronicle of events that passes for 
history as the term is ordinarily used 
he has in mind history the way it was treated by georg wilhelm 
friedrich hegel a german philosopher at the end of the 18th and 
start of the 19th centuries whose ideas influenced both hitler and 
stalin 
history in the hegelian sense is the clash of ideas over how 
mankind should order its affairs history says fukuyama has ended 
with the decline of communism because the major societies have 
stopped struggling over rival ideologies and reached a consensus 
about the ultimate system for governing themselves 
the winner democracy and capitalism 
thus the persian gulf conflict is a pinprick ideology is not at 
stake 
if fascism a defeated ideology once in competition with 
communism and democracy were to take root in the soviet union 
said fukuyama that would be historic 
in an interview fukuyama said it was wrong for persian gulf 
developments to get bigger headlines than the reunification of 
germany which he described as the event of the decade 
iraq is basically a country ruled by a tribe all relatives of 
saddam hussein like a mafia family resembling the politics of 
16thcentury italy he said 
and saudi arabia is a bureaucratic monarchy resembling the 
european state of five or six centuries ago 
i didnt say the world is going to be free of conflict 
fukuyama said 
but third world struggles simply are not over the principles 
that govern mankind 
fukuyama says he was misunderstood a year ago and if detractors 
would read more carefully they would find they are not even talking 
about the same thing 
fukuyamas essay which appeared in a small conservative 
quarterly the national interest concluded with a statement that 
perhaps this very prospect of centuries of boredom at the end of 
history will serve to get history started once again 
diplomats discussed his theory in plush places magazines in 
europe and asia translated his article and quoted him newspapers 
featured him in long essays his theory reached the status of a 
doctrine 
fukuyama who has spent most of his adult life on college 
campuses had worked for the state department for only a year 
his idea made its first appearance as the topic of a lecture 
delivered in chicago in 1988 it caught attention as a heavily 
footnoted 16page essay a year later the national interest ran 
learned rebuttals and comment in subsequent issues fukuyama got 
the last word with an eightpage goodnatured but firm reply 
the chicagoborn yale cornell and harvardeducated fukuyama 
now works for the rand corporation a private think tank during an 
earlier stint with rand in california he met his wife laura they 
have two young children 
he hopes to return to government but is busy these days turning 
endism into a book he avoids public appearances and works in 
an unmarked office strewn with books and papers struggling to 
meet a publishers deadline 
he dismisses speculation that his essay was intended to 
articulate a we won doctrine for the bush administration 
i am a relatively junior official with little impact on 
policy he said i am constantly amazed at the parochialism of 
the political class in washington 
fukuyama said his ideas were aimed at a professional audience 
and it surprised him when they were translated into 13 or 14 
different languages and set off little debates in places where you 
wouldnt expect it to happen portugal indonesia south korea 
lithuania the soviet union 
apparently people sensed that very great things were happening 
in the world he said 
he emphasized that what i have said is simply that liberal as 
opposed to authoritarian ideas won not any particular liberal 
country called the united states has won it does seem to me that 
we americans really have a lot of great problems economic 
primarily relative to other democracies 
of course there are countries at lower levels of development 
such as iraq but they are basically irrelevant to the grand 
historical process fukuyama said 
unlike nazi germany or the soviet union before mikhail 
gorbachev they dont challenge democracy as the ultimate standard 
for mankind 
but he noted that the soviet union offers fascism perhaps its 
best chance of revival writers in some russian journals speak a 
language unheard in europe for many years and are uncomfortably 
close to the soviet mainstream 
fukuyama made his debut as a congressional witness at a recent 
senate foreign relations committee hearing 
he told the senators it was an ironic accident of fate that we 
should be faced with a geopolitical crisis just as the cold war is 
ending allowing people to mistakenly feel that kind of world will 
be continuing 
</TEXT>
