<TEXT>
the accounting industrys rulemaking board has 
proposed that businesses supply more uptodate financial 
information to investors a move that could prove costly to 
companies battered by a soft economy 
the financial accounting standards board agreed late tuesday to 
propose requiring companies to disclose in footnotes in their 
financial statements the market value of many assets that are now 
merely shown at their original cost 
the new york times said the proposal would apply to nearly all 
categories of financial instruments including stocks bonds 
options and in the case of financial institutions customer 
deposits and loans 
the proposed marketbased accounting rule could prove costly to 
companies suffering in todays softening economy earlier this 
month fasb approved a farreaching change in the way businesses 
report healthcare costs for retired workers a move that has the 
potential to slash millions of dollars from comapnies financial 
earnings 
but the traditional approach scornfully dubbed 
onceuponatime accounting by critics may have little 
relation to actual worth in a slumping economy it has been faulted 
for contributing to the crisis facing financial institutions by 
letting them avoid revising loan portfolios to reflect falling 
values 
the proposal on market values is open to public comment for four 
months before it can be made final 
