<TEXT>
the shortterm outlook for the world economy has 
worsened markedly in recent months the organization of economic 
development and cooperation said in a major report thursday 
the organization of 24 major industrial democracies said in a 
twiceyearly report that the rise in oil prices has boosted 
inflation and curtailed output 
it said eastern european countries face special difficulties as 
they try to convert to market economies and it gave a gloomy 
assessment of the soviet unions economic health 
among the oecds own members the united states was repeatedly 
singled out as a cause of particular economic concern 
differences have become more accentuated between the buoyancy 
of activity in some countries notably japan and western germany 
and its weakness in a number of other countries including the 
united states the report said 
inflation remains under control in western germany and japan 
but is relatively high in the united states the report said it 
noted that the dollars weakness was contributing to inflationary 
pressures in the us economy 
the report said developments in the worlds financial markets 
have been disquieting 
equity prices have plunged and marketdetermined interest 
rates have risen in many countries only in part because of the 
gulf situation it said fragility persists in some sectors of 
us financial markets where banks are limiting credits to certain 
classes of borrowers and questions have risen about banks balance 
sheets in japan 
these developments together with the effects of higher oil 
prices have led to a less favorable view of the shortterm 
economic outlook than before the summer inflation is likely to be 
higher and output weaker 
the oecd projected that economic activity among its members 
could expand by 2 percent in 1991 picking up to 25 percent in 
1992 
it said unemployment would increase from 625 percent of the 
labor force in the first half of 1990 to almost 7 percent in 1992 
consumer price inflation was likely to be 6 percent annually in the 
first half of 1991 but could drop to under 45 percent by late 
1992 
the projections were based on an oil price of 27 per barrel and 
noted that if prices rose further the task of policy in 
containing inflation and supporting confidence would be harder 
the report also said 
government deficits in the united states and germany will be 
greater than expected the oecd estimated that the us deficit 
would be about 250 billion in fiscal 1991 and could increase the 
following year 
the recent us budgetcutting agreement will substantially 
strengthen control over public expenditure the report said 
nonetheless the federal government deficit is likely to remain 
large for several years 
global problems such as rising interest rates and higher oil 
prices will complicate the tasks of eastern european countries as 
they switch to market economies 
although reforms have begun output declined in 1990 in all 
these countries and is likely at best to stabilize in 1991 while 
inflation remains a widespread problem 
in the soviet union specific reform measures have not yet 
been agreed to let alone implemented the report added soviet 
output is falling inflation is accelerating and the trade 
balance could deteriorate 
the oecd said its members could help eastern europe by ensuring 
that their own markets were open 
more liberal trade policies would contribute to a more stable 
as well as more prosperous world the report said 
the member nations of the oecd are australia austria belgium 
britain canada denmark finland france germany greece 
iceland ireland italy japan luxembourg the netherlands new 
zealand norway portugal spain sweden switzerland turkey and 
the united states 
