<TEXT>
prudentialbache securities inc will report a 
1990 loss of about 250 million more than double what analysts had 
expected and a further sign of the malaise gripping wall street 
its parent said thursday 
the prudential insurance co of america also said it had 
injected 200 million in new capital into the struggling investment 
firm which has abandoned or reduced several key businesses in a 
major restructuring 
the equity infusion is the latest move by a big corporate parent 
this year to contain losses at firms pummeled by a collapse in 
merger activity and the junk bond market 
the securities industry has cut more than 50000 jobs nationwide 
since the 1987 stock market crash this year layoffs have been 
concentrated in highpaying jobs such as investment banking 
the anticipated 250 million loss at prudentialbache exceeds 
analysts forecasts of 75 million to 100 million including 1990 
prudentialbache has been unprofitable in three of the last four 
years the firm lost 51 million in 1989 
prudential an insurance and financial services company in a 
statement attributed the loss at its securities subsidiary to 
drastic cuts in four core areas intended to reduce exposure to 
unprofitable businesses 
prudentialbache in recent months laid off twothirds of its 
investment bankers or 120 professionals closed its risk arbitrage 
trading operation sold its canadian arm and reduced its limited 
partnership activities 
prudentialbache chairman george l ball said in a memo to 
employees that the firm had spent 370 million on costs associated 
with the reductions including severance payments he said the 
lower total loss indicates very healthy core profitability in our 
other activities 
in addition to the 200 million equity infusion the parent 
company said it was acquiring all of prudentialbaches merchant 
banking assets and that the business in the future would be managed 
by the parent 
spokesmen for the companies declined to say how much the 
merchant banking assets totaled the firm said it had a capital 
base of 16 billion and that the infusion was not made to meet 
federal regulatory requirements 
merchant banking is one of the areas hardest hit during the wall 
street slowdown it involves investing a firms own capital into 
merger deals often with risky junk bonds many of those 
transactions have soured because of the markets decline and the 
shaky status of many takeovers 
prudential insurance bought bache group inc in 1984 for 385 
million and has invested more than 1 billion into the securities 
firm which failed in an attempt to become an investment banking 
power and is returning to its retail brokerage roots 
prudential spokesman joe vecchione said the capital injection 
was a sign of support for the investment firm he said the company 
and ball have the full support of the prudential 
were longterm investors vecchione said were willing to 
weather downturns in the business 
prudentialbache which has 17000 employees down from 19000 a 
year ago said it would focus on its individual investor and mutual 
fund activities which made money in 1990 
in his memo to employees ball said the firm would highlight 
the burgeoning financial needs of affluent individual investors 
in the united states and abroad 
as part of its costcutting efforts prudentialbache this week 
confirmed it is negotiating with shearson lehman brothers inc to 
merge data processing operations for securities transactions firms 
expanded those operations in the 1980s but now have excess capacity 
because of a decline in the retail business since 1987 
perrin long an industry analyst with lipper analytical 
securities corp said the 200 million capital injection would 
improve prudentialbaches balance sheet and help broker 
recruitment because it was a sign of stability 
other companies have been forced to help bail out securities 
subsidiaries this year american express co injected more than 1 
billion and took full control of shearson and cs holdings pumped 
more than 700 million into cs first boston inc and assumed the 
bulk of the firms outstanding bridge loans from problematic 
merchant banking deals 
