<TEXT>
the dollar finished broadly higher thursday as 
traders sought a safe haven in the wake of the uncertainties 
created by the resignation of soviet foreign minister eduard 
shevardnadze 
gold prices rose in europe but retreated slightly in us 
trading on the new york commodity exchange gold bullion for 
current delivery settled at 38590 a troy ounce off 10 cents from 
wednesday later republic national bank quoted a late bid for gold 
of 38335 an ounce down 55 cents 
the dollar gained ground in european trading and continued its 
climb when dealings shifted to domestic markets 
though traders were buying dollars much of the days activity 
centered on selling the german mark on the theory that germany is 
more widely exposed to the economic and political climate in the 
soviet union than other nations 
germany has large loans outstanding to the soviet union and 
because of german monetary union there was great expectation that 
they would find a huge export market within the soviet union 
said michael malpede a senior analyst at refco group ltd in 
chicago 
john mccarthy chief dealer at amsterdam rotterdam bank in new 
york characterized trading as a flight out of germany rather 
than a flight to quality he predicted that we will have to see 
more disintegration in the soviet union before there is any real 
permanent effect on dollar trading 
still shevardnadzes resignation was dramatic enough to 
distract attention from the deepening us recession and declining 
interest rates lower interest rates generally are bearish for the 
dollar because they erode the value of fixedincome securities 
the move brings the market focus to the economic fundamentals 
of europe and takes some of the focus off the economic concerns in 
the us malpede said 
trading was active but typically thin ahead of the christmas 
holiday which accentuated the dollars advance 
