<TEXT>
business expectations for sales profits and 
employment in the first quarter of 1991 are at the lowest point 
since the 1982 recession said a quarterly survey released thursday 
by the dun amp bradstreet corp 
findings in the survey by the leading provider of business 
information were consistent with a broad array of other evidence 
that shows the nation has lapsed into a recession 
dun amp bradstreets salesoptimism index down 10 points in the 
last quarterly survey released after iraqs aug 2 seizure of 
kuwait fell another 14 points in the current survey of 1500 
business executives nationwide 
business optimism is down sharply said dun amp bradstreets 
chief economist joseph w duncan softness in the domestic 
economy coupled with the uncertainty on the international scene 
due to events in the middle east has pushed expectations to their 
lowest levels in eight years 
despite oilprice inflation caused by the middle east crisis 
duncan said most businesses do not see opportunities to increase 
their own prices so profit expectations have dipped to very low 
levels 
the survey showed sales optimism fell in every major industry 
group particularly in retailing which has been weathering a rough 
christmas selling season historically its most critical time of 
year 
expectations for higher employment in the first quarter of 1991 
also reflected the gloomiest outlook since the last nationwide 
recession the survey showed 
dun amp bradstreets latest survey conducted between nov 1 and 
nov 20 queried executives in manufacturing retailing and 
wholesaling on whether they expected an increase decrease or no 
change in firstquarter sales profits prices inventories 
employment exports and new orders 
based in new york dun amp bradstreet is the worlds largest 
marketer of business information and related services with 
worldwide revenue of 43 billion last year it has conducted the 
quarterly survey on business expectations since 1947 
in another economic report released thursday standard amp poors 
corp a leading creditrating concern said it expected a lower 
rate of inflation to be the one spot of good news in 1991 because 
of the nations economic weakness 
in a recession inflation rates come down along with 
everything else standard amp poors chief economist david blitzer 
said in its semiannual consumer price forecast we expect to see 
some of the smallest price increases since the mid1980s 
nonetheless blitzer said if war breaks out in the middle east 
oil prices could reach 40 or 50 a barrel vs the current level 
of the midtohigh 20s in other areas the standard amp poors 
forecast predicted air fares would rise along with higher fuel 
costs clothing and food prices would rise modestly and liquor 
tobacco and healthcare costs would rise sharply 
