<TEXT>
the nations spending on health care climbed 
to a record of more than 604 billion last year federal officials 
said thursday 
the growth rate accelerated in 1989 just as it has done every 
year since 1986 and the amount spent added up to roughly 2400 
for every man woman and child in the country 
the ability of society to meet other needs is affected by the 
growing share of economic resources claimed by health 
expenditures said gail wilensky chief of the health care 
financing administration in releasing the new data 
health and human services secretary louis sullivan said the 
growth in health costs is alarming it cuts some people off from 
medical care and puts a heavy financial burden on people who are 
using the system 
sullivan is leading a domestic policy council review of the 
nations health care system he has said he will present his 
recommendations after he evaluates two reports that are due out 
next year 
the secretary has rejected governmentfinanced national health 
insurance as a solution and said he favors continuation of a 
publicprivate system 
health spending in 1989 accounted for 116 percent of gross 
national product the total of all goods and services prdocued and 
was 111 percent higher than it was in 1988 the gross national 
product rose 67 percent over the same period 
the share of gnp was also a record as recently as 1985 the 
share was 105 percent 
federal spending on health programs in 1989 amounted to 147 
percent of the total federal budget of about 11 trillion up from 
141 percent of the previous years budget 
of the total spent on health care last year 33 percent was paid 
by private insurance 21 percent came from the pockets of 
consumers 17 percent was paid by medicare and 10 percent was paid 
by federalstate medicaid programs 
other government programs put in 15 percent and other private 
sources 4 percent according to the financing administrations 
figures 
the agency plans to publish a more detailed account of health 
spending next month 
it gave this breakdown of where each dollar went 
39 cents to hospitals 
19 cents to physicians 
8 cents to nursing homes 
22 cents was spent on dental and other professional services 
home health care drugs and vision products 
the remaining 12 cents paid for administration research and 
construction 
nearly 50 billion was spent on nursing home care of that 44 
percent of that was by paid directly by patients the great bulk of 
it 41 percent of the total out of social security income 
medicaid and medicare paid 51 percent of the bill and private 
insurance paid 1 percent 
overall percapita health spending would amount to 2360 based 
on an estimated 1989 population given by the health care financing 
administration of 256 million people however the census bureau 
has estimated that 1989 population was 248 million which would 
mean spending of 2435 per person the financing administration 
did not explain why it used a different population estimate 
