<TEXT>
a federal appeals court ruled thursday that 
eastern airlines before rehiring replacement pilots in training 
must rehire pilots who went out on strike last year 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals upheld a district court 
ruling that eastern may not hire new pilots who at the time the 
striking pilots agreed to return to work had not completed 
training and become certified by the federal aviation 
administration 
the ruling would displace about 200 of easterns 1900 pilots 
who were in training when the air line pilots association ended 
its strike in november 1989 also under the ruling no new trainees 
would be hired until all former strikers who wanted to return had 
been allowed to do so 
the union said as many as 800 pilots are seeking to get their 
jobs back 
eastern spokeswoman karen ceremsak said the miamibased company 
had not yet reviewed the ruling but planned to appeal 
alpa went on strike on march 4 1989 in a show of sympathy with 
striking eastern machinists eastern then began hiring and training 
new pilots 
in august 1989 many eastern pilots offered to return to work 
but eastern said no pilot positions were available to former 
strikers easterns response was the same when the remaining pilots 
ended the strike three months later 
eastern placed the former strikers on an inactive recall list 
for future positions and filed suit against alpa declaring that 
new hire pilots in training are permanent replacements who may 
not be deprived of active employments by strikers 
alpa argued that pilot trainees are not permanent replacements 
under the federal railway labor act until they fully complete 
training and operate their required regular flights 
the atlantabased appeals court agreed in thursdays ruling 
saying the newly hired pilots are not permanent employees because 
they were not qualified to perform the work easterns pilots 
ordinarily discharged 
first the former strikers unlike the trainees have actually 
flown regular revenue flights for eastern the threejudge panel 
wrote second the returning pilots are only required to complete 
requalification training substantially less than the time 
required to train and qualify the new hire pilots 
joel gay office manager for the alpas eastern local in 
atlanta said the union was pleased with the ruling we had been 
anticipating it all along so were not surprised were just 
happy 
gay estimated the number of former strikers wanting to return to 
work at between 250 and 800 
ms ceremsak said eastern was not sure how many alpa members 
jobs were at issue 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

