<TEXT>
cms energy corp said thursday it was 
taking a 450 million accounting charge against earnings to reflect 
costs it might not recoup on an unfinished nuclear plant resulting 
in a fourthquarter loss 
paul knopick spokesman for the dearbornbased corporation said 
company officials wouldnt speculate whether cms parent company of 
consumers power co will report a loss for the year 
cms reported a thirdquarter loss of 214 million or 26 cents 
a share and a profit of 145million or 178 a share for the 
first nine months of this year the company made 74 million in the 
fourth quarter of 1989 
the 450 million charge represents a move to unsnarl financial 
tangles from consumers aborted nuclear plant project at midland 
hyman said its not a loss that has anything to do with 
generating electricity 
cms stock closed at 27 a share up 175 thursday on the new 
york stock exchange 
cms announced the 450 accounting charge after receiving an 
administrative law judges recommendation thursday on its request 
to recover 214 billion in midland nuclear plant costs through 
rate increases 
administrative law judge robert e hollenshead recommended that 
the michigan public service commission let consumers impose 134 
billion in rate increases over 10 years 
if the commission adopts the recommendation which matches one 
by its staff the 450 million will go toward making up the 
difference between the amount requested and the amount granted 
knopick said 
consumers power spent 41 billion on the midland plant before 
construction was halted amid financing and legal problems in 1984 
</TEXT>
