<TEXT>
general motors corp on thursday announced a 
special oneyear effort to buy back some of its class h common 
stock from company officials who received the shares as part of 
their compensation 
gm spokesman bill winters said about 27 million shares of class 
h common stock may be eligible for the program about 88 million 
shares of class h stock are outstanding about 65 million of which 
are owned by howard hughes medical institute 
as many as 4800 gm managers worldwide are eligible to receive 
class h stock as part of their compensation winters said it was 
not possible to tell how many of the managers may still hold the 
stock he said 
gms class h stock is linked to its gmhughes electronics corp 
subsidiary 
winters said the company wants to repurchase the shares to have 
on hand for future employee compensation he said class h stock was 
not traded actively and the buyback would give managers an easy way 
to redeem their shares 
gm said it will repurchase the stock at market prices class h 
stock rose 25 cents thursday to close at 1875 on the new york 
stock exchange 
gm began repurchasing class h stock on the open market in 1987 
with a goal of buying about 10 million shares since then gm has 
repurchased about 46 million shares the automaker said that 
program will continue 
