<TEXT>
a federal bankruptcy judge thursday approved a 
bank letter of credit for federated department stores inc and 
allied stores corp to borrow money to buy merchandise from foreign 
suppliers in 1991 and 1992 
the judge vincent j aug jr also allowed federated to pay the 
state of indiana about 1 million in unpaid sales tax from late 
1988 and early 1989 federated lawyers told aug they are trying to 
get kentucky to pay back about 1 million in sales tax the retailer 
overpaid to that state 
the letter of credit from ibj schroder bank amp trust co of new 
york is good for 100 million and could be extended to 150 
million it is effective through feb 6 1992 and will replace a 
citibank letter of credit expiring feb 3 
the citibank credit was good for borrowings of as much as 150 
million the retailers have used 70 million of that amount so far 
federated spokeswoman carol sanger said 
federted and allied attorney cory lipoff said the new letter of 
credit should reassure foreign vendors that the companies 
retailing operations are healthy 
federated and allied both based in cincinnati and owned by 
campeau corp of toronto have been operating under bankruptcy 
court supervision since january 
lawyers for the retailers said indiana and kentucky 
inadvertently received each others tax payments from federated for 
sales at lazarus department stores from november 1988 to january 
1989 
federated said it didnt learn of the error until last june and 
has been trying to persuade kentucky to return the overpayment 
federated said it owes indiana 969676 which includes sales tax 
plus interest 
federated wants a reimbursement of 113 million from kentucky 
which has refused the request federated is threatening to bring 
the dispute into federal bankruptcy court if it isnt resolved 
federated and allied together employ about 110000 people and 
operate 255 stores in 28 states 
</TEXT>
