news corp ltd chief executive 
rupert murdoch said thursday he was pleased with progress on 
crucial debtrescheduling proposals but the international media 
groups stock value plunged 
murdoch issued a statement in reply to a query from the 
australian stock exchange after news corps share price plunged 
almost 23 percent to its lowest level this year the stock fell to 
420 austrialian dollars or 323 and later recovered to finish 
off 109 australian dollars or 84 cents at 435 australian 
dollars or 335 
in new york thursday the stock fell 87 cents to 750 
murdoch said he knew of no reason for the share slump and 
insisted a majority of bankers and other lenders had already 
indicated they agreed to news corps terms for a refinancing of 
688 billion in debt that comes due within the next three years 
analysts attributed much of thursdays share price fall to 
concern about a highly critical tv documentary to be shown on 
britains channel four thursday which concentrates on news corps 
financial position and its low tax payments 
the company is very peased with the progress of its 
negotiations for the rescheduling of the major part of the news 
groups debt he said 
earlier this month australian ratings downgraded news corps 
short and longterm debt close to default levels it described the 
groups financial position as extremely fragile and said its 
debts totaled 1066 billion 
the downgrade followed a similar move last month by usbased 
moodys investors service inc 
news corp executives have recently held meetings with bankers 
in australia the united states and europe murdoch plans to reduce 
debt levels through unspecified assets sales 
